00:26:42.479 --> 00:26:47.920
First, I just want to briefly clarify the difference between a model provider and an LLM,

00:26:47.920 --> 00:26:53.119
because this turns out to be important when talking about privacy and security. So the

00:26:53.119 --> 00:26:58.400
model provider is the company that hosts your model that you might be paying, or like where

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:03.439
you're getting your model from. So this is something like Anthropic or OpenAI. Or if

00:27:03.439 --> 00:27:06.479
you are using a local model, it might be something like HuggingFace.

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:11.599
And this is in contrast to the LLM itself. This is the actual model that generates the responses

00:27:11.599 --> 00:27:20.479
to your queries. Okay. This is important because LLMs themselves, the actual model, are stateless.

00:27:20.479 --> 00:27:28.239
They don't have any memory. They don't remember your prior requests. If I send some data over to

00:27:29.199 --> 00:27:35.359
an LLM, it is not storing that anywhere. It takes in that input, it generates a response,

00:27:35.359 --> 00:27:41.119
it sends that response back to me, but it does not store that information anywhere because of how

00:27:41.119 --> 00:27:50.079
the LLM itself works. They're stateless. You might be saying, you know, I know that's not true.

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:54.160
You can carry on a conversation with them and they'll tell you what they're doing.

00:27:54.479 --> 00:27:58.800
I know that's not true. You can carry on a conversation with them and they will remember

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:04.400
my prior request. And this is because each time you send a request to the LLM, it gets the whole

00:28:04.400 --> 00:28:10.959
conversation. So if you've had 15 back and forths at the 16th request, it's sending all those 15

00:28:10.959 --> 00:28:16.239
requests to the LLM. This happens each time. It's sending the entire content of the conversation.

00:28:16.239 --> 00:28:20.079
And you have to do that because of the statelessness of the LLM.

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:29.199
Okay. So this is good news for data privacy. However, your model provider may log and store

00:28:29.199 --> 00:28:34.319
your requests and use them for other purposes. So this is why I've tried to clarify the difference

00:28:34.319 --> 00:28:44.560
between these two. Okay. To make it a little bit more explicit, I have a diagram. So if we're

00:28:44.719 --> 00:28:51.280
talking about a tool like DataBot or Positron Assistant that can see your data, it can see

